segments.text: The Galveston storm was when?
Early September 1900.
Was it a hurricane?
Yeah, it was what we call a hurricane.
It was what we call a hurricane now.
And it was awful bad.
And there also had been...
a big storm and the Rattus River overflowed and that was bad.
And all the way around they just caught it.
Same year?
Well, not exactly the same year, but it was close to together.
And they just didn't know what to do and so they just moved off and left the whole thing.
Did they lose all their property?
Yes, it was finally sold.
I don't know how much.
And that is the money that... and we then spent a little money on a farm that's now called Mine at... Thornton?
Now, is there anything I haven't brought out that you would like for me to mention this afternoon?
Oh, no.
I can't think of anything right now.
How old were you?
Do you remember anything about the storm?
Do I remember the storm?
Yes, I remember it.
I remember how the wind blew.
Did it flood?
Oh, yes.
The seawall?
The water came in the house, and everything, and the rain blew.
I remember when the house blew.
It was a two-story block.
And I remember when it blew off the blocks, you know.
Nobody in the family was killed, were they?
Oh, no.
None of us were hurt.
That's a miracle.
None of us were hurt, but it blew all night.
And the next day, it was just as fire and calm as it could be.
That storm had lasted all night.
But the next day, it was...
just as far as could be.
And so, I believe, if there's anything else you want to... And so we left there, and oh, we got malaria, you know, from other mosquitoes.
How'd you get rid of that?
Oh, well, we didn't, and it's finally cost our lives.
He lived a few, well, two or three years.
But he died of what a doctor told me.
We called it black jaundice.
Somebody was interviewing me about some insurance.
And I said, how did... Mama, of course, was living with him.
How did our father die?
And I said, well, they said he had black jaundice.
And he says, honey, do you know what black jaundice is?
And I says, no.
Of course, I remember him.
I was nine years old.
I remember how he was affected.
Their kidneys turned to blood.
And I remember seeing him carry out those hot jars of bloody water.
And he lived about a week.
And he said it was acute.
This doctor told me, it was at March, this doctor told me that.
He's dead now.
It's one that Hegg called.
You know, Hegg had a sister named...
What was Ms. Collins' name?
Well, anyway, Dr. Collins' wife was Peg's sister.
And it was he that was talking to me about the insurance.
And he said it was a cuticle area that he died on.
I said, well, that was where?
He says, you didn't develop it there in this country.
I said, oh, no, we got it down there on the coast.
When did you move the car from down there?
from Angleton.
We came to, near Cossie, and you know, Cossie's not far from Thornton.
And there we stayed until, well, we came to Thornton.
And, oh, I'm so,
We jumped off one thing onto another.
We were talking about his death, you know.
He died at 52, you see.
He was an old man when he died.
And Clem looks more like him than any child he had.
Tell me about your school.
Where did y'all go to school over there?
I hadn't started school very big then.
We were on the way out in the country near, well we were at what near the school was, Eureka, between Cossie and Todd.
And Clem and Roy went to school.
Bird and Albert were high school age then.
And Clem and Roy went to school at Eureka.
It's about midway between them.
It's up there now, isn't it?
Yes, it is.
They don't have a school there anymore.
I think the schoolhouse may be there.
I don't know whether it's a community house or not.
It was a school there for many years.
They had a very good little country school.
And when I started to school, I went there to school.
But we didn't go along.
We later moved up to Thornton, near Thornton.
And there we went to our sister Dorcas taught this country school near Thornton.
It was called Mill Creek.
And there they went to school.
And we all did.
And she taught that year.
Maybe she taught two years.
I don't know.
Anyway, then the next school we went to was the Thornton School.
We have a picture of Clem's class in the Thornton School.
How old was he then?
Well, he looked grown, but of course he wasn't any older than the children in the class all looked.
And there were children, well, you didn't know, but your mother and daddy, your mother, grandmother did.
There was, oh, there was 10 or 12 of them.
And their professor, and the professor went from there to, he was a good teacher, went from there to Commerce, Texas to teach a little
It wasn't a summer school, but he went there to teach.
And he lived there a few years.
They just had one teacher?
In high school.
Just one teacher in high school.
And I was down in the grades.
And Roy was down, he was ahead of me, of course.
And so we have that picture.
And of those people in that picture,
that are living now, Clem is just about the only one that's left.
Dr. Kidd, Earl Kidd, made a dentist.
And he's been dead some time.
His wife lives in Dalton.
And now I'm just talking about the picture.
I don't know that you were even there.
Yeah, I might.
And then so many of those folks.
And Walter Sparks lived there, and he lived in Rosebeck, and he has died.
They're just about all dead with them.
How long did y'all go to school there?
Well, I went to school there off and on, practically all of my schooling, and I graduated from that school.
We didn't have them.
10 grades then.
And I graduated from that school when I was about 17.
And of course Clem and Roy both quit to work.
Clem was a good student.
I don't know about Roy, but I remember that.
They quit the farm?
Yes, to work on the farm.
You see, Albert left home.
Your granddaddy, Taylor, he was gone.
There wasn't much for folks on the farm then.
And so they quit the work.
So then I kept on going.
I went to school, and I drove a horse.
Drove a horse and buggy, or did you ride just the horse?
Horse and buggy.
I went on the horse, and I drove a horse for a mile.
And it would be about sunset when I get home in the afternoon.
How far were you from school?
How far was it?
It was about three miles.
But I just fooled along.
I didn't run in any hurry.
Mom could see me coming away in the distance.
Of course, that road is closed now that I came.
How many kids were in the school when you were in there?
How many kids were around that school?
Oh, I guess it was maybe 200 or 300.
That's a lot.
Well, it was a lot of kids.
It wasn't all bigger than the town was.
We thought it was bigger then, though, than it is right now.
I've heard Martin was a bigger guy then, too.
Yes, my father was.
And anything else you want to know?
Well, where did Ampop go then?
Well, where did he go to school?
I don't know.
What did he do when he quit school?
He went to school, I reckon, in Angleton.
He and Albert went to school in Angleton, I guess.
But they came with us when we left Angleton.
See, we came by wagon.
and brought the cows and the horses and everything.
When did he get married?
In what year?
Well, Clem will probably know that.
I don't know.
I was sure it was 1905.
He said it was either Christmas Day or Christmas Eve, whichever it was, but it was 1905.
Did he just move to Grosbeck and Big Hill then?
No.
See, we all lived near Thornton, as near Thornton as anywhere else.
It was our town.
And we lived off in the pasture.
And he had rented him a place for them to go to live over two or three miles to the west of us over in the neighborhood of, oh, well, I don't know who lives over there now.
But anyway, it wasn't too far away from
where we lived.
And so they got busy and mama gave them things and your grandmother, your
Your grandmother's folks gave them things, and they had, and he, Byrne had made a good crowd that year, and he bought them some furniture.
And they fixed it.
And a man, some folks named Watson owned the place where, I don't know who owns it now, but somebody named Watson owned it, and he was a very good father.
Well, did you go to college?
Well, yes.
And then I studied and I went to Trinity University.
Where was that?
It was in Waxahachie at that time.
It's been in San Antonio now for a number of years.
But that's where I went.
And then later, when I got my certificate, we didn't have to have a degree then to start.
We just had to have a certificate.
I kept on working, you know, and going to school, teaching and everything.
Did you teach all grades?
No, I never did teach a whole big grade.
My first school was at...
an orphanage near Itasca, Texas.
And that was in 1918.
And Clem was in the Army.
You see, he had to go to the World War I.
And that year, the old schools were terribly torn up at that time, of course, due to the
due to the war and everything.
And then later on I went to Baylor a lot and studied a lot one way or another.
Now anything else you want to know?
Well... Uncle Clem, can you tell me, you remember much about World War I and how you
Were you drafted?
Oh, yes, yes.
You were?
Did they send notices like they do now?
When was that?
Do you remember what year?
I guess it was June.
June 14th was when I went.
Well, where did you go first?
College Station.
Really?
College Station.
Was it on the campus?
Was it at College Station?
Where'd you go from there?
Did you get basic training there?
I was just a young man.
Went from Atlanta, Camp Jordan, St. John's, to Jacksonville, Florida.
Jacksonville?
Did you go overseas from there?
Yes.
Where'd you go?
I went overseas from Newport, New Virginia, you see.
They didn't have any place there to load any boats.
They took us to Newport, New Virginia.
Uh-huh.
What were your duties?
I mean, what did you have to do?
Uh-uh.
What's that?
Everything would destroy me.
I heard you went to France.
How long were you over there?
About six months.
Did you see any combat?
No.
We're in France.
We're in France.
Where are you?
How long were you over there?
Six months?
We discharged after the war?
No, after the war.
